Buckwheat is an interesting cereal, in Russia it's called "Greek grain", in Italy it's "Saracen grain", Czechs call it "pagan grain", other names are "Turk grain" and "Tatar grain" in Europe. In the East it's called "black rice". This has the same connotation as "gypsy summer"...

So if nothing else grows on the land, you can still sow some buckwheat. It got completely outclassed by potatoes after the 17th century which also grow anywhere no matter how poor the soil, but also give massive harvests. But buckwheat was a good grain, it has no gluten actually.

... or "Indian summer" in America, a warm period in autumn, "false summer". So buckwheat is fake grain. Why did they call it that? Buckwheat is able to grow on very poor soils where normal wheat cannot survive, but it also gives relatively poor harvests compared to anything else.

I wonder if there's a relationship between a plant's resilience and its healthful properties analogous to how when you cook/boil mushrooms for a long period of time the protective effects of their extract are not lost, but all toxic compounds are destroyed in the cooking process.

Plant toxins are generally destroyed in cooking, but most beneficial plant nutrients and compounds survive high temperatures. Potatoes grow on poor soils and are probably the best vegetable/starch with the ketoacids and all nutrients they have. I don't know if buckwheat is good.
I just read that part I'd guess there are like 100 diff things they call black rice

When I read this newsletter it left me wondering how women experience time during pregnancy and if a changed time perception means pregnancy is a good time for women to read long novels because they would be able to use the expectancy/planning system of the frontal lobes better.

I think people being unable to hold their attention for long without getting distracted which forces them to only be able to consume short form video content or (and e.g. leaves them unable to read very long doorstopper books) is related to a defect in time perception.

It reminds me of that quote attributed to Tolkien (he did not actually say it AFAIK) about how Narnia is not realistic because if a girl met a satyr in real life she would get raped instead of having a tea party. The knowledge of a seeming androgyne having a sexuality is scary.

There is nothing more disturbing to women than unwanted and unexpected sexuality. Like a girl who talks to an old lonely man from her neighborhood and asks him for his phone number to trade recipes or something and he proceeds to send her pictures of himself naked. It's horror.

This is also why a certain type of figure who is usually an older family man, often in an authority role like a professor, who is very open and straightforward, and plain in a way that reveals he has no hidden desires in his subconsciousness is generally very comforting to women.

I remember a girl here posting about how she had a really cute wholesome-looking old man taxi driver, but when she looked at his phone he was sexting porno chatbots on Whatsapp or something like that and it horrified and depressed her. Lecherousness means everyone is a satyr.
